<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900521-0064</DOCNO><DOCID>900521-0064.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Entergy Corp.:   New Orleans Rejects Plan   To Purchase Utility Unit</HL><DATE>05/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   ETR</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><LP>   Entergy Corp. said the New Orleans City Council voted toreject a buy-out plan under which the city could haveacquired the company's New Orleans Public Service Inc. unitand certain other properties for more than $700 million.   The utility holding company previously said it wouldrather not sell the assets. The buy-out plan was made under alongstanding &quot;perpetual right&quot; held by the city allowing itto purchase New Orleans Public Service assets at any time.</LP><TEXT>   Under the proposal, the utility would have become cityproperty, but Entergy management would have continued tooperate it for five years. New Orleans Public Serviceprovides electricity to about 192,000 customers and gas toabout 159,000 customers in that city.   A proposed financing package called for the issuance ofmore than $850 million of revenue bonds, on which paymentswould be about $8 million a month for 20 years. A counciladvisory committee estimated that consumers would save about$8 a month under the plan.</TEXT></DOC>